During the course of this project I encountered a couple of anomolous
behaviors with the BUILD and RESORC programs.

BUILD will not let you insert the names of the official supported DEC
devices into the active system unless the handler name is correct for
that device.


.RUN SYS BUILD

$PRINT

KL8E: *TTY  
LPSV: *LPT  
PT8E:  PTP   PTR  
CSD : *SYS  *CSD0 *CSD1 
CSDN:  CSD0  CSD1 *CSD2 *CSD3 *RKA  *RKB   DTA0 

DSK=CSD:CSD1
$INSERT CSDN,DTA0
DTA0 NOT FOUND
$

This was the previous version of CONSYS.PA before changing the DTA0 to
DTA.  DTA0 is clearly there.  For this reason when you mount an RK05 or
DECtape image on the CSD server the device is referenced as RKA:, RKB:,
and DTA: instead of RKA0:, RKB0:, and the DTA0: names.  This may cause
less confusion in the situation where a real RK05 exists on a machine.

And then there is RESORC.  RESORC is supposed to tell you what devices
are available to a running OS/8 system.  However it uses inside
knowledge of DEC devices to display some of its information.  User
defined devices do not show up correctly.  Here is an example.


.RESORC /E

96 FILES IN 1530 BLOCKS USING 3 SEGMENTS
2509 FREE BLOCKS (2 EMPTIES)

#  NAME TYPE MODE SIZ BLK KIND U V ENT USER
01 SYS   40  RWF      SYS      0 A  07
02 DSK   40  RWF      SYS      1    41
03 TTY  TTY  RW       16+ KL8E   E 176
04 LPT  LPTR W        17  LPSV   C  05
05 HC    40  RWF      SYS      0 A  07
06 HD    40  RWF      SYS      1    41
07 HE    40  RWF      20         A  42
10 HF    40  RWF      20         A  43
11 SK   RK8E RWF 3248 20  RK05 0    20
12 RXA3 RK8E RWF 3248 20  RK05 0    21

FREE DEVICE SLOTS: 05,  FREE BLOCK SLOTS: 05
OS/8 V3Q


Entries 05 through 10 should be displayed as CSD0 through CSD3.  RESORC
displays its internal table identifiers of HC through HF instead.
Entries 11 and 12 should be RKA and RKB but because they are trying to
look like an RK05 it is confused somewhat.  It does know the size of
the device at 3248 which was what I was going for when I built that
entry but it thinks the TYPE is RK8E instead of CSD which is what I
told it.  I don't have a working RK05 to put on the system to test but
I expect that there could be some problems if a real RK05 is mixed
with the CSD version.

This probably goes back to the fact that OS/8 maintained compatibility
with PS/8 file systems.  PS/8 did not have BUILD so the tables necessary
to know this stuff were not stored anywhere.


When making my initial csd0 image I found out that BUILD does something
both clever and unexpected.  When it copies the system image from the
running system to the new system disk it does so with the following
algorithm:

1) Read a block from SYS:
2) Copy last page of Field 0 to a temporary page.
3) Install the new SYS handler in the last page of Field 0.
4) Write the block read in step 1 to SYS:
5) Copy back the running SYS handler saved in step 2.

This is repeated for every block that needs to be copied.

This was a problem for me since the csd server cannot distinguish
between devices for the read in step 1 and the write in step 4 since
they both come from the SYS: entry point at 07607.  I was able to work
around this by using PIP to copy the system blocks and allowed BUILD
to think it had worked when in fact all it did was read and then write
the same block back to the original SYS image.

The downside of this is that BUILD cannot be used to make a bootable
image on a different device because as far as csd is concerned it is
writing to the same device as it is reading from.  The only way to fix
this is to have the handler send a device identifier as part of the
request.  The problem is that the CONSYS handler has no space to add this
functionality.  If the CSD1: entry point is removed from CONSYS: this
only frees up two words and I think it will take at least 3 words.
Note: This only applies when trying to build a SYS image on a CSD virtual
device.  If one of the devices is real hardware you should be ok.
